  "prompt": "Which kind of guitar should I buy as an amateur?",
  "response": "Choosing your first guitar depends on several factors, including your musical preferences, budget, and whether you want to play electric or acoustic music. Here are some options based on different criteria:\n\n### Acoustic Guitar\n1. **Best for Beginners**: \n   - **Yamaha FG800**: Known for its great sound and playability, this is a solid choice for beginners.\n   - **Fender CD-60S**: Another fantastic option with a comfortable neck and quality construction.\n\n2. **Budget-Friendly**: \n   - **Jasmine S35**: An affordable yet reasonably good acoustic guitar.\n   - **Epiphone DR-100**: A solid entry-level model with good sound.\n\n### Electric Guitar\n1. **Best for Beginners**: \n   - **Squier by Fender Affinity Series Stratocaster**: Great for versatile playing styles and easy to handle.\n   - **Yamaha Pacifica Series**: Adjustable and versatile, making it perfect for beginners.\n\n2. **Budget-Friendly**: \n   - **Monoprice 6116**: A highly affordable option that offers great value for the price.\n   - **Ibanez GRG121**: Solid build and good playability at a low price.\n\n### Things to Consider\n- **Body Type**: If you're choosing an acoustic guitar, consider whether you want a dreadnought (larger sound) or a concert/folk size (smaller and easier to hold). For electric, think about the shape and feel of the guitar.\n- **Neck Size**: Make sure the neck feels comfortable in your hand. \n- **Sound Preferences**: Try different guitars to see what sound resonates with you. \n- **Budget**: Set a budget and try to stay within it, keeping in mind that you might also need an amplifier (for electric guitars), tuner, picks, and other accessories.\n- **Used vs. New**: Consider buying a used guitar; you can often find good quality instruments for lower prices.\n\n### Final Tip\nTry visiting a local music store where you can test out different guitars. Playing them in person will give you a better idea of what feels comfortable and sounds good to you. Happy playing!",
